{"id":14881755,"mediaExerciseId":"06e2b7f1-5a8b-4ac0-8dbc-7cef70e42e8a","exerciseName":"4","chapterName":"21","chapterTitle":"International Corporate Finance","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"21.4","sectionTitle":"Interest Rate Parity, Unbiased Forward Rates,and the International Fisher Effect","pageNumber":725,"solutions":[{"id":5966792,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to define covered interest arbitrage and  international Fisher effect.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":61,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/96489d64d93fabf1ec878f47219288a6/76e30dc817dfb92a933805af2a714647/lateximg_large.png","width":1055},"regular":{"height":32,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/96489d64d93fabf1ec878f47219288a6/76e30dc817dfb92a933805af2a714647/lateximg.png","width":528}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"## 4a.\n\nWe are asked to define the covered interest arbitrage.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"A **covered interest arbitrage** refers to two investments that are risk-free creating an arbitrage opportunity and needed a forward contract to prevent an exchange rate risk.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":105,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/96489d64d93fabf1ec878f47219288a6/2ae97fbf0d907d895a0084c37fac417b/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/96489d64d93fabf1ec878f47219288a6/2ae97fbf0d907d895a0084c37fac417b/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"The term *covered* refers to the arbitrage activity being covered in the exchange rate changes since the forward exchange rate was locked.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/96489d64d93fabf1ec878f47219288a6/3482571c56b7085d21c55bb9af511b49/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/96489d64d93fabf1ec878f47219288a6/3482571c56b7085d21c55bb9af511b49/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"## 4b.\n\nWe are asked to define an International Fisher Effect.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"**International Fisher Effect** is a theory that real interest rates *are equal* across countries. That is to say, if one country have higher real return than the other, money would flow out of the latter. Hence, it is important that real rates are equal to ensure the flow of money across the countries.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":143,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/96489d64d93fabf1ec878f47219288a6/9b1e2be39064e28df549659751b4dee7/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/96489d64d93fabf1ec878f47219288a6/9b1e2be39064e28df549659751b4dee7/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"As a conclusion, we have defined covered interest arbitrage and  international Fisher effect.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":61,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/96489d64d93fabf1ec878f47219288a6/3cee4a9d9efac023684ab16fc0d1127c/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":32,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/30/96489d64d93fabf1ec878f47219288a6/3cee4a9d9efac023684ab16fc0d1127c/lateximg.png","width":498